Since the system dump is enabled only on selected systems and dependency on back-end support, it better to set default as disabled. Also this approach will help to disable dump incase the system doesn't support this settings.

The enabling of system dump is based on specific feature flags and is limited to systems that support this functionality. The disabling of this feature is mainly intended for debugging scenarios, such as when developers or customer engineers need to perform live debugging on the system.

In field operations, the system dump functionality is enabled by default. This is part of our strategy to collect as much data as possible in the case of a failure. Based on that strategy I think even if the settings cannot provide the actual value, we have to collect the system dump during failure scenarios.

This ensures we don't miss critical debug data due to a support service failure.
Adding a comment in the function

Yeah, makes sense to me, if someone has enabled system dump for their platform, but then we can't read the setting to determine if they've run a workaround to disable it, we should just assume enabled. PHYP would be very mad if we had some timing issue with the phosphor-settings service and didn't generate their dump.
